    {
      "id": "200.1.01",
      "q": "Dorsal and ventral rami are similar in that they both contain sensory and motor fibers.",
      "options": [
        "True",
        "False"
      ],
      "answer": 0,
      "explain": "and watch where the terminology shifts. Both dorsal and ventral rami are mixed — they carry both sensory and motor fibers, yes. But Now things get truly spectacular: Dorsal ROOTS are sensory, ventral ROOTS are motor. Once they merge into rami, though? Both carry mixed traffic. The terminology is trying to trip you up. Let me show you exactly where the transformation happens.",
      "mechanism": {
        "title": "Spinal Nerve Anatomy: Roots vs. Rami",
        "content": "Navigate with me: And Observe carefully now: Closely — this is one of the most exquisite anatomical transformations in the nervous system. A spinal nerve forms from the union of a dorsal root (sensory) and a ventral root (motor). This combined spinal nerve is very short — it almost immediately divides into a dorsal ramus (heading to the back) and a ventral ramus (heading to the front and limbs). Both rami carry fibers from both roots, making them mixed nerves. It's a brief merge-and-split operation. The signal streams recombine and redistribute. Invite this in: Of it.",
        "metaphor": "Walk through this: On this. Think of it like a highway interchange. Sensory traffic (dorsal root) and motor traffic (ventral root) merge briefly at the spinal nerve junction, then split again into two highways — dorsal ramus heading to the back, ventral ramus heading everywhere else. But now — wait for it — each highway carries both types of traffic. The segregation dissolves. The streams intermingle. Pure physiological poetry."
      },
