    {
      "id": "200.1.02",
      "q": "A patient has an injury of the spine and is now suffering from a loss of motor function in his right arm. However, he still has normal sensory function in the arm. Based on this, the nervous tissue damage is likely located at ___.",
      "options": [
        "The dorsal rootlets at one of the thoracic vertebra",
        "The ventral root at one or more of the cervical vertebra",
        "Spinal nerves of the cervical vertebra",
        "The dorsal root at one or more of the cervical vertebra"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explain": "Let me walk you through the darkness of this injury. Motor loss with sensory intact — that precision tells us everything. The ventral roots carry motor fibers OUT to muscles, the outbound command cables. Cervical level, not thoracic, because the arm is innervated by the brachial plexus (C5–T1). The deficit reveals the location. Walk this path: And I'll show you why this patient can still FEEL his arm but cannot MOVE it. Devastating, isn't it?",
      "mechanism": {
        "title": "Dorsal vs. Ventral Roots: The Functional Segregation",
        "content": "Join me in examining this: Spinal nerve organization follows the Bell-Magendie law: Dorsal roots are sensory, ventral roots are motor. This segregation is absolute at the root level, And this is the masterstroke: DORSAL ROOT contains axons of sensory neurons. Damage means sensory loss, numbness, loss of proprioception. VENTRAL ROOT contains axons of motor neurons. Damage means motor loss, paralysis, muscle atrophy. SPINAL NERVE — after roots merge — carries both fiber types, so damage here affects both modalities. The patient loses everything distal to the injury. Grant yourself this moment of clarity: The pattern of deficit reveals the location of damage. The body speaks in anatomical maps.",
        "metaphor": "Thread this needle carefully: And I'll show you the doors. The dorsal root is the 'in-door' — sensory signals entering the spinal cord. The ventral root is the 'out-door' — motor commands leaving the spinal cord. Damage one door, and traffic in that direction stops. But the other door still works. Now — What follows is exquisite — damage the hallway after they merge (the spinal nerve), and all traffic stops. Both doors lead to darkness. Evolution's crowning achievement in its terrible logic."
      },
      "isotopes": [
