    {
      "id": "200.1.03",
      "q": "Starting at the spinal cord, the subdivisions of the brachial plexus are (in order) ___.",
      "options": [
        "Trunks, divisions, cords, and roots",
        "Divisions, roots, trunks, and cords",
        "Roots, divisions, cords, and trunks",
        "Roots, trunks, divisions, and cords"
      ],
      "answer": 3,
      "explain": "Travel deeper into this: And I'll teach you the mnemonic that will save you: 'Robert Taylor Drinks Cold Beer' — Roots, Trunks, Divisions, Cords, Branches. A neural spaghetti junction that surgeons have nightmares about. Allow the mechanism to reveal itself: : Five spinal levels reorganizing into one unified arm control system. The body's quiet genius. The body's own telecommunications network.",
      "mechanism": {
        "title": "Brachial Plexus Organization: A Neural Spaghetti Factory",
        "content": "Press onward: Factory. The brachial plexus reorganizes fibers from five spinal levels (C5-T1) into specific peripheral nerves through a series of mergers and splits. Let me walk you through each stage — Follow the breadcrumbs: ROOTS are the ventral rami of C5-T1, the starting cables. TRUNKS: C5+C6 merge into superior trunk, C7 continues as middle trunk, C8+T1 merge into inferior trunk. DIVISIONS: Each trunk splits into anterior (flexor territory) and posterior (extensor territory). The anterior/posterior split defines functional domains, not just anatomical regions. CORDS are named by position relative to the axillary artery — lateral, medial, posterior. BRANCHES are the terminal nerves like musculocutaneous, median, ulnar, radial, axillary. Now — here's the truth of the biology, and it's devastating: This reorganization allows fine motor control and provides redundancy. Damage to one root doesn't completely paralyze the arm — but severe brachial plexus injuries, like motorcycle crashes that tear multiple roots from the spinal cord, are catastrophic. Total arm paralysis. Let that sink in.",
        "metaphor": "Keep this momentum: And I'll show you the telecommunications routing center. Five trunk lines (roots) come in from different exchanges. They're sorted, combined, and redistributed through several switching stages until they finally emerge as specific circuits (branches) that each serve a particular destination — the biceps, the thumb, the wrist extensors. Cut one trunk line early, and you lose some function. But tear out the whole routing center? The arm goes dark. Complete blackout. Sublimely intricate"
      },
      "isotopes": [
        "physiology.general"
      ],
      "category": null,
      "chapter": "Chapter 13 — Nerves & Sensory",
      "scaffoldFile": "200.1-spinal-scaffolds/200.1.03-scaffolds.json",
