    {
      "id": "200.1.05",
      "q": "The correct simple spinal reflex arc is: ___.",
      "options": [
        "Receptor, afferent neuron, integration center, efferent neuron, effector",
        "Receptor, efferent neuron, integration center, afferent neuron, effector",
        "Effector, efferent neuron, integration center, afferent neuron, receptor",
        "Effector, afferent neuron, integration center, efferent neuron, receptor"
      ],
      "answer": 0,
      "explain": "Move with me toward this: And follow the signal flow. The reflex arc is beautifully linear: Receptor → Afferent (sensory) neuron → Integration center (spinal cord) → Efferent (motor) neuron → Effector (muscle/gland). Stimulus to response in milliseconds. No conscious thought required — or even possible at this speed. Your spinal cord decides. Your brain finds out later. Absorb this: Into that reality.",
      "mechanism": {
        "title": "The Reflex Arc: Speed Through Simplicity",
        "content": "Set out toward this: Reflexes are fast because they minimize processing and bypass conscious control. Let me show you the simplest reflex — the monosynaptic stretch reflex (knee-jerk) — which has only ONE synapse: The sensory neuron from the muscle spindle synapses directly on the motor neuron that contracts the muscle. Stimulus → detection → response in about 50 milliseconds. Here's the delicious truth: Your brain doesn't even know it happened until after the muscle contracts. Consciousness is always late. Most reflexes are polysynaptic, with interneurons allowing more complex responses — withdrawal reflexes, for instance, require coordinated inhibition of antagonist muscles. But even those are fast because they're pre-wired circuits in the spinal cord. Now — Persist through this, because Now for the piece de resistance: And fascinating: After spinal cord transection (complete severing), reflexes below the injury site initially disappear (spinal shock), then gradually return over weeks to months. But they're often hyperactive because descending inhibitory signals from the brain are gone. The spinal cord can generate reflexes autonomously, but without brain input, it loses refinement. Embrace this: Clinical reality: Patients with complete spinal cord injuries have reflexes in paralyzed limbs — muscles contract in response to stimuli, but the patient can't feel it or control it. The circuits work. The communication doesn't. Designed with precision.",
        "metaphor": "Track each step: And I'll show you the emergency protocol. The reflex arc is like a pre-programmed emergency response. The receptor is the smoke detector, the afferent neuron is the alarm wire to the fire station, the integration center is the dispatcher (who might just route the call directly to a truck, or coordinate multiple units), the efferent neuron is the radio call to the trucks, and the effector is the firefighters spraying water. Here's the beautiful logic: In a true emergency, you don't wait for the mayor to approve the response — you use the pre-authorized protocol and act immediately. Speed through simplicity. Survival through automation. Crafted to perfection."
      },
      "isotopes": [
        "neurology.receptor"
      ],
      "category": null,
      "chapter": "Chapter 13 — Nerves & Sensory",
