    {
      "id": "200.1.06",
      "q": "A patient presents after a spinal cord injury with loss of pain and temperature sensation on the LEFT side below the lesion, but motor weakness and loss of proprioception/vibration on the RIGHT side below the lesion. This clinical pattern suggests damage to ___.",
      "options": [
        "The entire left half of the spinal cord (Brown-Séquard syndrome)",
        "The entire right half of the spinal cord (Brown-Séquard syndrome)",
        "Only the spinothalamic tract bilaterally",
        "The dorsal columns bilaterally"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explain": "Chart this course: Into one of neurology's most exquisite puzzles — the hemisection syndrome. Different sensory pathways cross at different levels. Pain/temperature fibers cross immediately after entering the cord (in the anterior commissure), then ascend in the spinothalamic tract. But proprioception/vibration fibers ascend IPSILATERALLY in the dorsal columns before crossing in the medulla. Motor tracts descend and cross in the medulla before reaching the cord. Now Track this carefully: When you cut the RIGHT half of the cord: You lose motor and dorsal column function on the RIGHT (same side), but spinothalamic function on the LEFT (opposite side). The crossing patterns create this beautiful dissociation. This is the signature of Brown-Séquard syndrome, and it reveals exactly where the anatomy breaks.",
      "mechanism": {
        "title": "Brown-Séquard Syndrome: The Hemisection Dissociation",
        "content": "Journey with me into this: Into one of the most beautiful lesions in clinical neurology. Brown-Séquard syndrome results from damage to one lateral half of the spinal cord — a hemisection. The resulting deficits reveal the anatomy of crossing patterns: IPSILATERAL deficits (same side as lesion): Motor weakness/paralysis (corticospinal tract), Loss of proprioception and vibration (dorsal columns), Loss of all sensation at the level of the lesion (because nerve roots are damaged). CONTRALATERAL deficits (opposite side): Loss of pain and temperature sensation (spinothalamic tract). Now — This is where physiology becomes poetry — the LEVEL matters. Pain/temperature loss begins 1-2 segments BELOW the lesion on the opposite side (because fibers cross after ascending a segment or two). Proprioception loss begins AT the level of the lesion on the same side. Surrender to the logic here: Localization: If you know the sensory levels, you can pinpoint the lesion. The crossing patterns create a neurological signature. Common causes: Penetrating trauma (stab wounds, gunshots), spinal cord tumors (especially meningiomas pressing from one side), hematomyelia (bleeding into half the cord), multiple sclerosis plaques. Pure Brown-Séquard is rare; partial variants are common. But when you see it, you KNOW where the damage is. The anatomy writes the diagnosis.",
        "metaphor": "See this through: And I'll show you the split highway. Imagine the spinal cord as a highway with multiple lanes of traffic, some northbound, some southbound. Now cut the highway in half vertically — right down the middle. Traffic in the right lanes (motor commands, proprioception) going to the right side of the body is blocked. But traffic in those same right lanes carrying pain from the LEFT side (because it already crossed over) is also blocked. So the right body loses motor and position sense, while the left body loses pain sensation. The crossing patterns create this beautiful, terrible asymmetry. The body splits along functional boundaries. Beautifully inevitable"
      },
      "isotopes": [
        "physiology.general"
      ],
      "category": null,
      "chapter": "Chapter 13 — Nerves & Sensory",
