    {
      "id": "200.1.07",
      "q": "A patient presents with bilateral loss of pain and temperature sensation in the hands and upper arms, forming a 'cape-like' distribution across the shoulders, but proprioception, vibration sense, and motor function are intact. This pattern most strongly suggests ___.",
      "options": [
        "Bilateral dorsal root damage at cervical levels",
        "Damage to the central part of the spinal cord affecting the spinothalamic tracts as they cross (syringomyelia)",
        "Complete transection of the spinal cord at cervical level",
        "Bilateral damage to the dorsal columns"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explain": "Let's explore this together: Cord, where a cavity can form and slowly expand, and Follow this thread — this is syringomyelia, and it's devastating in its precision. The central canal is exactly where pain and temperature fibers CROSS from one side to the other (in the anterior commissure). A fluid-filled cavity expanding outward from the center damages these crossing fibers FIRST, creating bilateral loss of pain/temperature in a segmental distribution while sparing the dorsal columns (which are posterior) and corticospinal tracts (which are lateral). The result? A suspended sensory level, often in a cape distribution. The patient can still FEEL touch and position but not pain or temperature. They burn themselves, cut themselves, without realizing. This is called 'dissociated sensory loss,' and it's pathognomonic for central cord pathology.",
      "mechanism": {
        "title": "Syringomyelia: The Central Cavity That Dissociates Sensation",
        "content": "Venture here: Spinal cord, and Track with me here — this is a slow catastrophe. Syringomyelia is a condition where a fluid-filled cavity (syrinx) forms in the central canal of the spinal cord and gradually expands. Most commonly associated with Chiari malformation (where the cerebellar tonsils herniate through the foramen magnum, disrupting CSF flow), but also seen after spinal trauma or tumors. Here's where the anatomy becomes exquisite: The syrinx expands from the center outward, damaging structures in a predictable sequence. FIRST STAGE: The anterior commissure is destroyed — these are the crossing fibers for pain and temperature (spinothalamic pathway). Result: BILATERAL loss of pain/temperature in a segmental, cape-like distribution (often C4-T1). But touch, proprioception, and motor function remain intact initially. This is dissociated sensory loss. SECOND STAGE: The cavity expands into the anterior horns (motor neuron cell bodies). Result: Lower motor neuron signs — weakness, atrophy, fasciculations in the hands. The classic 'claw hand' deformity. THIRD STAGE: The cavity expands laterally into the lateral corticospinal tracts and sympathetic neurons. Result: Spastic weakness below the lesion, Horner's syndrome (if sympathetic chain affected at T1-T2). Now — here's the clinical tragedy, and it's heartbreaking: Early syringomyelia is often painless and slowly progressive. Patients don't notice the loss of pain sensation until they've accumulated scars from unnoticed burns, cuts, and injuries. They develop painless arthropathy (Charcot joints) in the shoulders. The diagnosis is often delayed for years. MRI shows the cavity beautifully — a dark CSF-filled space in the cord. Treatment is surgical decompression to halt progression. Permit yourself to feel this: This one lesion reveals the geography of the cord — where crossing happens, where motor neurons live, where pathways run. The pathology is a dissection tutorial.",
        "metaphor": "Keep pace with this: And I'll show you the expanding water balloon. Imagine the spinal cord as a cable with multiple fiber bundles running through it — some carrying pain signals that cross in the center, some carrying touch/position signals that stay on the same side, some carrying motor commands in the outer layers. Now imagine a water balloon slowly inflating in the very CENTER of the cable. It cuts the crossing wires first (pain fibers), then expands into the motor control wires (anterior horn), then eventually reaches the outer layers (corticospinal tracts). The damage pattern reveals the internal geography. By the time the balloon is big enough to affect everything, the center has been destroyed for years. Stunning, yes? In its slow inevitability?"
      },
      "isotopes": [
        "physiology.general"
      ],
      "category": null,
      "chapter": "Chapter 13 — Nerves & Sensory",
