    {
      "id": "200.1.09",
      "q": "A patient presents with bilateral loss of proprioception and vibration sense in the legs, but pain and temperature sensation are intact. The patient has a wide-based, unsteady gait and positive Romberg sign (increased instability when eyes are closed). This pattern suggests selective damage to ___.",
      "options": [
        "The spinothalamic tracts bilaterally",
        "The dorsal columns bilaterally",
        "The anterior horns bilaterally",
        "The lateral corticospinal tracts bilaterally"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explain": "Descend with me into this: Columns, where position sense lives, and Don't lose this thread — this is one of the most elegant clinical syndromes in neurology. The dorsal columns carry proprioception (position sense) and vibration exclusively. Damage here causes loss of these modalities while sparing pain and temperature (which travel in the spinothalamic tract anterolaterally). The result? The patient can FEEL pain and temperature in their legs, but they don't know where their legs are in space. They can't stand with eyes closed (positive Romberg) because they rely entirely on vision to compensate for lost proprioception. They walk with a stomping, wide-based gait, watching their feet. This is called sensory ataxia, and the pattern reveals the anatomy. Classic causes: Vitamin B12 deficiency (subacute combined degeneration), tabes dorsalis (tertiary syphilis), multiple sclerosis. Receive this insight: Beauty: They can feel, but they can't locate.",
      "mechanism": {
        "title": "Dorsal Column Syndrome: When Position Sense Disappears",
        "content": "Walk this path: Spinal cord, where the body's internal GPS lives, and Maintain this focus — this is one of the most specific and devastating sensory syndromes. The dorsal columns (fasciculus gracilis medially for lower body, fasciculus cuneatus laterally for upper body) carry three related modalities: Proprioception (position sense from joints and muscles), vibration (rapidly adapting mechanoreceptors), and fine discriminative touch (two-point discrimination, texture). These large-diameter, heavily myelinated fibers enter through the dorsal root and ascend IPSILATERALLY in the dorsal columns to the medulla, where they synapse in the nucleus gracilis and cuneatus, then cross as the medial lemniscus. Here's where the anatomy becomes exquisite: Bilateral dorsal column damage causes a distinctive clinical syndrome: SENSORY DEFICITS — Loss of position sense (proprioception), loss of vibration sense, loss of fine touch discrimination (astereognosis — can't identify objects by touch), but preservation of pain and temperature (because spinothalamic tract is spared). MOTOR CONSEQUENCES OF SENSORY LOSS — Sensory ataxia: Uncoordinated movement due to loss of proprioceptive feedback. Wide-based gait, watching feet while walking, stomping gait. Positive Romberg sign: Instability increases dramatically when eyes are closed (because visual compensation is removed). Pseudo-athetosis: Slow writhing finger movements when eyes are closed (loss of position sense causes involuntary drift). Now — here's where the clinical causes reveal the vulnerability: Vitamin B12 deficiency (subacute combined degeneration): Damages dorsal columns AND lateral corticospinal tracts — produces ataxia plus spasticity. Tabes dorsalis (tertiary syphilis): Damages dorsal roots and columns — produces 'lightning pains,' Argyll Robertson pupils, and sensory ataxia. Multiple sclerosis: Demyelinating plaques preferentially affect heavily myelinated tracts like dorsal columns. Friedreich's ataxia: Genetic degeneration of dorsal columns and spinocerebellar tracts. Here's the heartbreak, and it's devastating: These patients retain pain sensation (they can feel injury) but lose proprioception (they can't sense body position). The result? They injure themselves repeatedly — painless joint damage (Charcot joints), burns, falls — because they can't coordinate movement without looking. They feel pain but can't locate its source precisely. They feel the world but can't navigate it. Invite this in: The internal map is erased, but the alarm system remains. They know something is wrong; they just don't know where they are.",
        "metaphor": "Pursue this logic: And I'll show you the building with no interior lights. Imagine you're in a building where all the lights are off, but you have functional pain sensors (you'd feel if you walked into a wall). In a normal building, you'd use your proprioceptive sense — your internal awareness of body position — to navigate in the dark. But now that sense is gone. You can only navigate if you can see (vision). The moment someone turns off the lights (closing your eyes), you're helpless. You bump into things, stumble, fall. You feel the pain when you hit the wall, but you couldn't prevent it because you didn't know where your body was in space. That's dorsal column damage. The external sensors (pain) work. The internal GPS doesn't. Truly remarkable."
      },
