    {
      "id": "200.1.10",
      "q": "A patient develops sudden paralysis and loss of all sensation below the waist after an abdominal aortic aneurysm repair. Pain and temperature sensation return partially after a few days, but motor function, proprioception, and vibration sense remain absent. This pattern suggests ___.",
      "options": [
        "Complete spinal cord transection with early recovery",
        "Anterior spinal artery occlusion sparing the dorsal columns initially but then damaging them",
        "Anterior spinal artery occlusion affecting the anterior two-thirds of the spinal cord",
        "Posterior spinal artery occlusion affecting only the dorsal columns"
      ],
      "answer": 2,
      "explain": "Accompany me through this: Anatomy of the spinal cord, and Walk through this — this is a surgical nightmare. The anterior spinal artery supplies the anterior two-thirds of the cord, including the corticospinal tracts (motor), spinothalamic tracts (pain/temperature), and anterior horns (motor neurons). The posterior one-third (dorsal columns) is supplied by paired posterior spinal arteries. When the anterior spinal artery is occluded — often during aortic surgery when intercostal arteries are ligated — you get immediate loss of motor function and ALL sensation. But wait for it — the spinothalamic tracts are more resilient to ischemia than the motor pathways. Pain/temperature sensation partially recovers as the penumbra recovers, but the motor pathways (corticospinal tracts) and anterior horn neurons are dead. The dorsal columns are spared because they have a separate blood supply. Open your mind to this: Pattern: The patient regains the ability to feel pain but not to move. They feel everything but can do nothing.",
      "mechanism": {
        "title": "Anterior Spinal Artery Syndrome: A Vascular Catastrophe",
        "content": "Press onward: Supply of the spinal cord, and Continue the sequence — this is where vascular anatomy meets devastating clinical reality. The spinal cord receives blood from three longitudinal arteries: One ANTERIOR SPINAL ARTERY (single, midline): Formed from branches of the vertebral arteries, runs along the anterior median fissure, supplies the ANTERIOR TWO-THIRDS of the cord. This includes: Anterior horns (motor neurons), lateral corticospinal tracts (motor pathways), spinothalamic tracts (pain/temperature), autonomic neurons, anterior/lateral white matter. Two POSTERIOR SPINAL ARTERIES (paired, posterolateral): Arise from vertebral or posterior inferior cerebellar arteries, run along the posterolateral sulcus, supply the POSTERIOR ONE-THIRD of the cord. This includes: Dorsal columns (proprioception/vibration), dorsal horns (sensory processing), posterior white matter. Here's the critical vulnerability: The anterior spinal artery is a WATERSHED territory — it has limited collateral supply. It's fed by segmental radicular arteries from intercostal and lumbar arteries, with the ARTERY OF ADAMKIEWICZ (great radicular artery) being the largest contributor, typically arising from T9-L2. During aortic surgery, trauma, aortic dissection, or prolonged hypotension, the anterior spinal artery can occlude, causing ANTERIOR SPINAL ARTERY SYNDROME: ACUTE PRESENTATION (within hours): Bilateral motor paralysis below lesion (corticospinal tracts and anterior horn infarction), Bilateral loss of pain/temperature (spinothalamic tract infarction), Loss of bladder/bowel control (autonomic pathway infarction), PRESERVED proprioception and vibration (dorsal columns spared). SUBACUTE EVOLUTION (days to weeks): Partial recovery of pain/temperature sensation (spinothalamic tracts have better collateral supply and penumbra recovery), Motor paralysis remains (motor neurons are highly vulnerable to ischemia; irreversible infarction), Transition from flaccid (spinal shock) to spastic paralysis (chronic UMN syndrome), Dorsal column function remains intact throughout. Here's the heartbreak: The patient transitions from being completely numb and paralyzed to being paralyzed but able to FEEL everything. They regain pain sensation but not motor function. They know where their legs are (proprioception preserved) but can't move them. The sensory world returns; the motor world doesn't. Risk factors: Aortic surgery (especially when intercostal arteries are sacrificed), Aortic dissection or aneurysm rupture, Prolonged hypotension, Spinal cord embolism (e.g., from cardiac surgery). Allow the mechanism to reveal itself: Tragedy: This is often an iatrogenic injury — a known risk of saving someone's life during aortic repair. The surgeons know the artery of Adamkiewicz is at risk. They try to preserve it. Sometimes they can't. The patient survives the aneurysm but is paralyzed. Thread this needle carefully, because here's the bitter truth: There's no good treatment once it happens. The infarction is irreversible. Rehabilitation focuses on adapting to permanent paralysis. The vascular anatomy is unforgiving.",
        "metaphor": "Follow the breadcrumbs: And I'll show you the city with two power grids. The spinal cord is like a city with two separate electrical grids — one for the front two-thirds of the city (anterior spinal artery), one for the back one-third (posterior spinal arteries). The front grid powers the motor systems (corticospinal tracts), the alarm systems (pain/temperature), and the autonomic systems (bladder/bowel). The back grid powers the positioning systems (proprioception/vibration). Now imagine the main power line to the front grid is cut during construction work (aortic surgery). The front two-thirds of the city goes dark — motors stop, alarms fail, autonomic systems shut down. But the back third keeps running on its separate grid — the positioning systems still work. Over a few days, some backup generators kick in for the alarm systems in the front (pain/temperature partially recovers), but the motors stay dead (irreversible infarction). The city can sense its position, feel pain, but it can't move. Simply magnificent. Perfect architectural tragedy?"
      },
